<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 12:23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BJP Winning Majority in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- India's right-wing Bharatiya Janata  
Party will probably return to power with more strength than ever, 
winning the most seats in parliament, according to an exit poll 
Sunday at the end of the monthlong elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The party led by Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee is expected  
to win 184 seats on its own and 287 with its 21 allies, giving it a 
clear majority of the 543 elected seats in the lower house of 
Parliament, according to state-run Doordarshan television. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll showed the main opposition Congress Party and its  
allies with 174 seats. 
</P>
<P>
	A clear majority for the BJP indicates that it could stay in  
power for a full five-year term. India has had three elections 
since 1996 because of unstable governments. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll, conducted by Development Research and Associates, has  
a margin of error of 1 percent, and was based on interviews with 
34,000 voters in 155 election districts across India. 
</P>
<P>
	Vote counting begins Wednesday, and a clear trend is expected to  
emerge by Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The BJP had two seats when it first entered Parliament in 1984.  
It gained strength on a platform of Hindu nationalism. However, 
with Vajpayee at the helm of a coalition government, the party has 
not pursued many of its more radical issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The election was called because Vajpayee lost a confidence  
motion by one vote in April, when a member of his unwieldy 
coalition defected. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can take some satisfaction that with a difficult election  
with limited forces ... it's gone off very well,'' said Election 
Commissioner Manmohar Singh Gill. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 605 million Indians were given the opportunity to vote in  
the world's biggest democracy. 
</P>
<P>
	While violence marred the election -- with about 95 people killed  
since the voting process began Sept. 3 -- that death toll was far 
below past elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Most deaths came in clashes between rival party supporters and  
in attacks by separatist militants trying to enforce election 
boycotts. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill said 56 percent of the 133 million people eligible to vote  
Sunday had cast their ballots. Half a million troops, police and 
officials deployed in 10 states to ensure safe, free and fair 
elections. But 39 people died over the weekend, most of which were 
blamed on separatists rebels in three northeastern states. 
</P>
<P>
	A handful of constituencies must still vote Monday, Tuesday and  
on Oct. 28, because flooding, ballot fraud or candidates' 
assassinations forced postponement. But a new parliament is 
expected to be seated by the middle of the month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
