<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 10:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 1989 San Francisco Quake Lookback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Paul Cobb was standing in his bedroom  
when he heard the Cypress Freeway come crashing down in a welter of 
concrete, metal and blood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody ran out in the street, people started saying, 'Look  
at the freeway! Look what has happened!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb ran to help people who had life enough left to squirm out  
of their mangled cars. Without time to think, he and many other 
residents of West Oakland, a largely black, mostly poor 
neighborhood, rose up in a united rescue effort, hauling out 
ladders, climbing atop the wrecked freeway, getting medical help. 
</P>
<P>
	It was one of the shining stories of the disastrous 1989  
earthquake that shook the San Francisco Bay area 10 years ago this 
month, killing 67 and leaving $7 billion in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	In the back of Cobb's mind that dreadful day, another rescue  
effort was born: At last, a chance for West Oakland to crawl out of 
the shadow of the hated elevated freeway that had loomed over the 
neighborhood for decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-eight hours after the quake, a group of city leaders and  
neighborhood activists met in the dignified grey-and-white dining 
room of Cobb's restored Victorian home. 
</P>
<P>
	By meeting's end, said Cobb, they had a plan -- ``Now that Mother  
Nature's shaken her hips and caused the freeway to fall, this is an 
opportunity to reroute it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	From the beginning, the Cypress Freeway was a hated symbol of  
power and powerlessness. It went up in 1957, slicing West Oakland 
into two. Suburban commuters thundered along its concrete 
shoulders; urban residents lived beneath, sucking in carbon 
monoxide fumes and resentment. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents fought against it without success.  
</P>
<P>
	``The world you live in today as far as black people was not the  
world we lived in then,'' said Bill Love, who was a teen-ager when 
the Cypress went up, linking the Bay Bridge and San Francisco to 
Interstate 880 and the southeastern suburbs. 
</P>
<P>
	After that, businesses dwindled and died. The neighborhood, an  
eclectic mix of mansions and humble railroad cottages perched on 
the lip of the San Francisco Bay, turned into a dusty relic. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was dirty, it was noisy, it divided West Oakland into two  
areas -- below and above,'' said Love. ``It was of no benefit to 
those of us who lived in West Oakland.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The world came crashing to a stop on Oct. 17, 1989. The  
7.1-magnitude quake struck as the Oakland A's were about to play 
the San Francisco Giants in the World Series, wreaking havoc 
throughout the bay area. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventy miles south in Santa Cruz, falling buildings killed  
three people. More died in San Francisco's upscale Marina district. 
</P>
<P>
	But the quake hit hardest at the Cypress, where 42 people were  
killed in a concrete avalanche when the top deck thundered down on 
the lower roadway. 
</P>
<P>
	Gloria Taylor, who lives in a housing complex 30 feet from the  
old freeway, rushed outside to marshall neighborhood children to 
safety. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were saying, 'But Mrs. Taylor, the ground is moving.' I  
told them to just keep moving,'' she said. She shooed the children 
inside, but they were already crying. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had seen people under this freeway, they knew that before  
this freeway crashed, people were there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some of those who came running to help lived on the fringe of  
society. 
</P>
<P>
	``Street people, who were the ones who were in tennis shoes,  
scaled that mess of concrete to save lives and there were dozens of 
them,'' said Cobb, who remembers standing on the ground marveling 
at their daring. 
</P>
<P>
	``Guys that people looked at as winos were climbing up the  
freeway,'' said Ralph Williams, the unofficial ``Mayor of West 
Oakland.'' The early rescuers helped people down and directed 
official rescue teams to survivors. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were actually very, very heroic,'' Love said.  
</P>
<P>
	There were other heroes. Buck Helm, the tough stevedore who  
survived 89 hours buried in the rubble and held on for 28 days in 
the hospital. Six-year-old Julio Berumen, whose leg had to be 
amputated to free him from the car where his mother died. 
</P>
<P>
	People remembered something else, too -- how a forgotten  
community risked life and limb to come to the aid of strangers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the whole world looked at this neighborhood, they  
remembered those people were climbing on the structures trying to 
save these folks,'' said Warren Widener, a county supervisor in 
1989. ``I think that they said that this neighborhood deserved 
more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	In 1957, neighborhood activists battered futilely against the  
doors of bureaucracy. In 1989, they knew some of the people inside. 
</P>
<P>
	Backed by allies like Widener, Oakland Mayor Lionel Wilson and  
Congressman Ron Dellums, ``For the first time we had the 
opportunity to pick up the telephone and say, 'We don't want to do 
this,''' said Love. 
</P>
<P>
	They showed they were serious early on, going to Washington to  
talk to transportation officials and hiring their own engineers. 
</P>
<P>
	It took the best part of a decade and about $1 billion, but in  
July 1997, the new freeway opened, a single deck skirting most of 
West Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the old freeway is gone, West Oakland's troubles  
aren't over. 
</P>
<P>
	Years of industry have left contaminated soil, and crime is  
still high. But new roads will soon link the neighborhood with the 
thriving shops and restaurants of next-door Emeryville, and new 
people are moving in. 
</P>
<P>
	On a sunny afternoon, Cobb and his friends were all smiles as  
they walked past the site of the old freeway. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is where it used to be,'' they said, gesturing to a  
grassy expanse that is awaiting landscaping improvements. For Cobb, 
the view is a pleasant one. 
</P>
<P>
	``At first what we had was a nightmare that divided us all with  
this poisonous air,'' he said. ``Now the air is clear and we have a 
field of dreams.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
