<HEADLINE> Froemming Umping One-Game Playoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bruce Froemming, the National League's senior  
umpire, will work behind home plate for Monday night's one-game 
playoff between the New York Mets and Cincinnati Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	Froemming, 60, joined the NL staff in 1971 and has worked four  
World Series, nine league championship series, three division 
series and two All-Star games. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerry Davis, in his 16th year, will work at first base. The rest  
of the crew has Mark Hirschbeck (12th year) at second, Ed Rapuano 
(10th year) at third, Rich Rieker (fifth year) in left and Jeff 
Nelson (first year) in right. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson was hired by the NL at the start of this season.  
</P>
<P>
	Froemming worked the plate Sunday during the Mets' 2-1 win over  
Pittsburgh. Hirschbeck was at second and Nelson at third. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
