<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Politics 2000 Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate Sen. John  
McCain said Sunday that recent events in Congress show lawmakers 
are tainted by the current campaign finance system. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of us have been corrupted by the process where big money  
and big influence -- and you can include me in that list -- where big 
money has bought access, which has bought influence,'' McCain said 
on ABC's ``This Week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As an example, the Arizona senator cited a proposal by House  
Republicans to tinker with a tax credit for the working poor. 
Spreading the Earned Income Tax Credit payment over a year rather 
than paying out a lump sum would save $8.7 billion in fiscal 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lately, we've got hundreds of billions of dollars in special  
tax breaks for special interests. So, what do we decide -- how do we 
decide to save money? Go after the Earned Income Tax Credit, which 
is for lower income working Americans who have no representation in 
Washington,'' said McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain last week joined a second GOP presidential hopeful, Texas  
Governor George W. Bush, in condemning the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain long has supported banning the unlimited soft money  
contributions corporations and other organizations now can make to 
political parties. 
</P>
<P>
	In an earlier interview on ``This Week'', Christian Coalition  
leader Pat Robertson said he could not support McCain for president 
because McCain's position on campaign finance religious group's own 
ability to make campaign contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	``That particular initiative would actually gut the Christian  
Coalition and a number of other citizen groups,'' Robertson said. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican Elizabeth Dole said Sunday she is  
unique among next year's candidates for president and commander in 
chief: She is the only one to have led a branch of the armed 
forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole headed the Coast Guard in the 1980s as President Reagan's  
secretary of transportation. The Coast Guard is under the 
Transportation Department during peacetime but in war comes under 
the Pentagon's control. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked on ``Fox News Sunday'' to explain why she would be a  
better commander in chief than another GOP presidential hopeful, 
Sen. John McCain, a former Navy pilot and prisoner of war, Dole 
said: 
</P>
<P>
	``You may be speaking of gender, and let me say that I think  
there are a lot of men who are not prepared to be commander in 
chief. I think you have to look at what sort of experience I have, 
and whether I'm prepared to be president of the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She made clear she was not belittling McCain's military bona  
fides: ``Of course he does have that experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But her experience, she added, ``includes a great deal of  
foreign policy in terms of each of the positions I've held. ... 
I've served as the first woman to head a branch of the armed 
forces, the United States Coast Guard when I was secretary of 
transportation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole said she also has plenty of executive experience, which is  
what the presidency is about. 
</P>
<P>
	She entered government as President Nixon's consumer adviser in  
1971 and after her 4 1/2 years in Reagan's Cabinet served as President 
Bush's secretary of labor. She resigned as president of the 
American Red Cross to make her White House run. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Christian Coalition leader Pat Robertson said  
Sunday his organization would not support a Republican presidential 
candidate who chose a pro-choice running mate. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be the kiss of death,'' Robertson said on ABC's  
``This Week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said he believes conservative Christian voters would  
not even be swayed on that point by a GOP candidate with a strong 
chance of beating the Democratic nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	``A great many people would stay home and wouldn't vote, or  
they'd vote to a third party,'' Robertson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson, the religious broadcaster who commands a grassroots  
army of 2.1 million Christian activists, has said he will not 
endorse any presidential candidate during the primary season. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he has made some preferences clear, and on Sunday again  
said he thinks Texas Gov. George W. Bush would make ``an acceptable 
candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, however, was not exempt from Robertson's admonishment  
about appointing a pro-choice running mate. ``I would promise him 
he would lose the election,'' said Robertson. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain of Arizona, another GOP presidential contender,  
said abortion should not be the defining issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the choice for running mates should have a  
litmus test associated with it,'' McCain said on ``This Week'' 
after Robertson's appearance. ``I think we should look at their 
overall record.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
