<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Dole: Woman Can Lead Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- If she wins the presidency, Republican  
Elizabeth Dole said Sunday, her sex will have no bearing on her 
ability to serve as commander in chief. She said she already has 
been the only woman to lead a branch of the armed forces, the Coast 
Guard. 
</P>
<P>
	Anyway, Dole said on ``Fox News Sunday,'' being president is  
about executive experience, of which she said she has plenty. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole headed the Coast Guard in the 1980s as President Reagan's  
secretary of transportation. The Coast Guard is in the 
Transportation Department during peacetime but in war comes under 
the Pentagon's control. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked to explain why she would be a better commander in chief  
than another GOP presidential hopeful, Sen. John McCain, a former 
Navy pilot and prisoner of war, Dole said: 
</P>
<P>
	``You may be speaking of gender, and let me say that I think  
there are a lot of men who are not prepared to be commander in 
chief. I think you have to look at what sort of experience I have, 
and whether I'm prepared to be president of the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, she said ``of course (McCain) does have that  
experience,'' but added: ``My experience includes a great deal of 
foreign policy in terms of each of the positions I've held. ... 
I've served as the first woman to head a branch of the armed 
forces, the United States Coast Guard when I was secretary of 
transportation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole's first government job was as President Nixon's main  
consumer adviser. She was President Bush's secretary of labor and 
resigned as head of the American Red Cross to run for president. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
