<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Unveils New Campaign in N.H. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOVER, N.H. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore brought his retooled  
campaign to New Hampshire on Sunday, calling himself the underdog 
in the presidential primary race against Bill Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	``The race has changed and it's now a two-person race that is  
close and hard-fought,'' Gore told reporters after a closed-door 
pep talk with supporters. ``I have always thought if Bradley passed 
the threshold of credibility and competence, then it would narrow 
dramatically and he did that, and so it's narrowed dramatically.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore spoke to key supporters from around the state at his Dover  
headquarters. From outside, loud cheering was heard several times 
during his remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	When the media was allowed in, Gore was moving through the room,  
shaking hands and joking with supporters and posing for photos. 
</P>
<P>
	Some said he seemed like a new person. Others said he was the  
same Al Gore they had seen before, but one who gets a bad shake 
from the media. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, he didn't look different,'' said Mary Frost of Gilford.  
``I have always thought he gave a very warm passionate approach. 
I've always wondered why people could label him as wooden.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the media,'' said a companion.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's got to be, because he is very warm,'' Frost agreed. ``He  
listens to people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's staffers took pains in previous New Hampshire visits to  
keep the candidate away from reporters, but Sunday, after his 
private meeting, he entertained a series of ``exclusive'' 
television interviews, then answered a handful of questions in an 
impromptu news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore repeated his challenge for a series of debates with Bradley  
soon; to wait until January would leave too little time before the 
primaries begin, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If (Texas Gov. George) Bush is the nominee on the Republican  
side ... Democrats are going to have to win on the issues and we 
need to get a head start and draw people toward a good healthy 
discussion of ideas,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
