<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Deals With Revenue Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- The Brazilian government's economic  
team faces a tight deadline to come up with a package of taxes and 
spending cuts to compensate for revenue lost after court rulings 
declared two new taxes unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	The reform-minded government of President Fernando Henrique  
Cardoso needs to make up almost $1.3 billion in revenue after the 
Supreme Court stuck down a tax on civil service pensions and a 
higher top tax bracket for active workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The taxes were part of package of fiscal adjustments promised by  
Brazil last year in its agreement with the IMF to qualify for $41.5 
billion credit line to shore-up its ailing economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sao Paulo Stock Exchange dropped 2 percent on news of the  
court decision and the dollar strengthened against the real, but 
government reassurances Friday allowed markets to stabilize. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am convinced that domestic and international investors will  
know that we have this commitment and the question will resolve 
itself over time,'' Finance Minister Pedro Malan told reporters 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Malan and his team are expected to have the new compensatory  
package of tax increases and budget cuts ready by week's end, local 
media reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues from the rejected taxes would have covered less than 10  
percent of the $10.5 billion deficit which the system is expected 
to generate next year. 
</P>
<P>
	However, it was held by the government to be an important step  
toward badly needed pension reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's 918,000 retired civil servants receive benefits many  
times greater than private sector retirees. 
</P>
<P>
	The average monthly pension of those retired from the federal  
judiciary is about $2,783 a month, compared with $126 a month for 
private sector retirees. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
