<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Davis' Injury Bad News for Denver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The defending Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos have plenty of  
problems. Their woes intensified with an injury to 1998 NFL MVP 
Terrell Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	While the severity of Davis' right knee injury wasn't  
immediately known, Broncos coach Mike Shanahan said after Sunday's 
21-13 loss to the New York Jets it looked as if Davis might have 
torn his anterior cruciate ligament. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it happened, they said there was some looseness in his  
knee,'' Shanahan said. ``We're going to keep our fingers crossed 
that it's not an ACL. But at this time, it looks like it could 
be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis was scheduled for tests Monday morning. A ruptured ACL  
would mean his season is over. A partially torn ACL would sideline 
Davis at least for several weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, who got off to a slow start after leading the NFL in  
rushing last season with 2,008 yards, was hurt in the first quarter 
during an interception return. Broncos offensive tackle Matt Lepsis 
made a diving tackle to cut down Victor Green at the sideline, but 
Lepsis also caught Davis on his right knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis was helped by trainers on the sideline, and then limped to  
the locker room. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, San Diego defeated Kansas City 21-14 despite losing  
quarterback Jim Harbaugh and wide receiver Jeff Graham on 
consecutive plays. 
</P>
<P>
	Harbaugh left with a bruised right elbow late in the first  
quarter, and the Chargers didn't crack the 100-yard mark until the 
third period. They finished with just 132 yards, and netted only 3 
yards on two possessions in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	On the first play after Harbaugh was hurt, backup Erik Kramer  
threw a long pass to Graham. The pass was broken up by Eric 
Warfield, and Graham hit his head on the turf. He was diagnosed 
with a concussion, but he came back late in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore Ravens offensive tackle Jonathan Ogden was carried off  
the field on a stretcher with a neck injury after diving into a 
pile for a loose ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Ogden sustained a severe neck ``stinger,'' but had full motion  
in his arms and legs, the team said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-8, 315-pound Ogden was injured at the end of the  
first half of a 19-13 overtime victory over the Atlanta Falcons. A 
bad snap in the shotgun formation sent quarterback Stoney Case 
scurrying for the ball at the Baltimore 20. Case recovered, but 
Ogden rolled over a pile of players and landed on top of Falcons 
lineman Lester Archambeau. Medical officials strapped Ogden to a 
backboard, stabilizing his neck, before being placed on the 
stretcher. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the half, the Falcons lost quarterback Tony Graziani,  
who sustained a concussion on a hit by Ray Lewis. Graziani, in the 
game because of Chris Chandler's hamstring injury, did not return 
and was replaced by third-stringer Danny Kanell. 
</P>
<P>
	New Orleans quarterback Billy Joe Hobert, driven off the field  
after being hit in the head twice on a touchdown run, suffered a 
neck sprain and cervical ``stinger.'' X-rays were negative, and 
Hobert will be re-evaluated Monday. He was replaced by Billy Joe 
Tolliver, and the Saints lost 14-10. 
</P>
<P>
	Hobert was hit in the head and left shoulder by Chicago Bears  
linebacker Sean Harris as he crossed the goal line. He continued 
running and took a helmet-to-helmet hit on the top of his head from 
Bears linebacker Rico McDonald. His head snapped to the side from 
the impact. 
</P>
<P>
	Hobert rolled over on his back, grimacing, and lay on the field  
for almost 15 minutes while he was examined by medical personnel 
from both teams. He was moving his hands and feet when he was on 
the ground, and he was opening and closing his fingers while he 
left the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacksonville RB Fred Taylor reinjured his hamstring and sat out  
the second half of the Jaguars' 17-3 victory over Pittsburgh. The 
same injury forced him to miss the Tennessee game. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same game Davis was injured, Jets cornerback Otis Smith  
fractured his left shoulder, and Jets linebacker Chad Cascadden did 
not return after suffering a knee injury in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota kick returner David Palmer sat out the second half  
with bruised ribs, but the Vikings went on to defeat Tampa Bay 
21-14. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
