<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Reds, Brewers Begin 8 Hours Late </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- While the New York Mets were saving their  
playoff lives, the Cincinnati Reds could only wait -- and wait, and 
wait. 
</P>
<P>
	Steady sheets of rain pounded County Stadium in Milwaukee at the  
scheduled 4 p.m. EDT start time of Cincinnati's season finale 
against the Brewers. 
</P>
<P>
	After more than eight hours of solid rain, the majors' last  
scheduled game in the 1999 regular season got underway at 9:52 p.m. 
EDT, a delay of 5:47. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds needed to win to avert a stunning collapse in the  
season's final weekend and force a one-game playoff with the Mets 
on Monday at Cinergy Field. Cincinnati controlled its own playoff 
destiny two days earlier, but consecutive losses to the lowly 
Brewers let the Mets back in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	When Cal Eldred finally threw the first pitch to Pokey Reese, a  
crowd of perhaps 500 die-hard fans, bundled up in winter coats, 
roared their approval. The Brewers, who thought the game would be 
the last ever played at County Stadium before July's crane accident 
at Miller Park, sold more than 55,000 tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	It was 45 degrees at gametime, and some players wore stocking  
caps in the dugouts. Many of the players' frosty breath could be 
seen. 
</P>
<P>
	The grounds crew applied drying agents to both the infield and  
the outfield, and the NL, desperate to finish the season on time, 
approved the game's start. But the field was far from being in 
shape, with inches of standing water throughout the outfield. 
</P>
<P>
	Right fielder Dmitri Young lost his footing and took a nasty  
spill near the foul line in the first inning, though he suffered 
nothing worse than soaked uniform pants. 
</P>
<P>
	Houston's victory over Los Angeles on Sunday clinched the NL  
Central title for the Astros (97-65). The win closed out Cincinnati 
from the division title. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds, who looked battered when they left the field Saturday  
after their 10-6 loss to the Brewers, watched the Mets-Pirates and 
Dodgers-Astros games on clubhouse televisions. The Brewers showed 
the game on the stadium's video screen for the few thousand fans 
who braved the elements. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds weren't anxious to play the game after the delay,  
particularly given the swampy nature of the outfield. Cincinnati 
manager Jack McKeon ventured into the outfield with umpires several 
times during the rain delay to test the turf, and appeared to be 
trying to convince crew chief Dana DeMuth that the game should be 
called. 
</P>
<P>
	A few Brewers players wandered out into the steady downpour  
about an hour before the scheduled start time to sign autographs 
for several hundred fans wearing ponchos and slickers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Twins-White Sox game 90 miles south in Chicago finished in a  
1-1 tie called after 6 1/2 innings because of a rain. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
