<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen early Monday  
following the release of a central bank survey showing further 
optimism about Japan's economy. Tokyo stock prices slipped. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was trading at 104.64 yen on the foreign exchange  
market, down 1.30 yen from its level of 105.94 late Friday in Tokyo 
and also below its late Friday level of 104.96 yen in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 25.28 points,  
or 0.14 percent, to 17,687.28. On Friday, the index climbed 107.10 
points, or 0.61 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar fell against the yen after  
Japan's central bank said Monday that business confidence at major 
manufacturing companies improved sharply during the past three 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	In its closely-watched quarterly ``tankan'' survey, the Bank of  
Japan said sentiment among large manufacturers had brightened over 
the last survey to a figure of minus 22 from minus 37, it's biggest 
improvement since November 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	The tankan measures the percentage of firms seeing business  
conditions improve minus the percentage seeing conditions worsen. 
The bank surveyed 9,275 companies for the latest report. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro bought 112.84 yen Monday morning,  
down 0.60 yen from its level late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In stock trading, share prices fell after opening higher, on  
concern that the yen's rise may hurt Japan's nascent economic 
recovery, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The tankan ``figure was better than expected, but basically the  
Japanese economy is not so strong,'' said Yoshihiko Kuroichi, 
manager of the research department at Kankaku Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen hurts Japanese exporters as their products become  
more expensive overseas, and thus less competitive. Gains by the 
yen also reduce the value of foreign revenue when repatriated to 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 1.01 points, or 0.07 percent, to 1,514.07. 
The TOPIX closed up 8.25 points, or 0.55 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average closed  
at 10,273.00 points, down 63.95. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.6350 percent from Friday's finish of 1.6750 percent. Its price 
rose 0.35 point to 100.56. 
</P>
<P>
 *(ep) 
</P>
</TEXT>
