<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Oct. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Koreans Protest Alleged U.S. Killings  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Waving signs and chanting, a South  
Korean student group rallied in downtown Seoul today, demanding 
that the United States punish those responsible for the alleged 
mass killings of civilians by U.S. forces at the start of the 
Korean War. It was the first public reaction from South Korea's 
largest student group regarding last week's news report on the 
alleged killings in July 1950. Last week, The Associated Press 
reported accounts by American veterans that their unit killed a 
large number of civilians at No Gun Ri, South Korea, during the 
early days of the Korean War. The villagers say 400 died. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Stands by Campaign Manager  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore said today his campaign  
chairman, Tony Coelho, is ``doing a great job'' and will stay on 
despite a government report that found questionable financial 
management while Coelho directed the U.S. pavilion at the 1998 
world's fair in Portugal. ``He is staying, and I haven't seen this 
report, but I know him and he is going to continue doing the 
terrific job that he's been doing as my campaign chair,'' Gore told 
CBS. Gore called Coelho a ``close friend'' and said he did not 
think Americans would see the charges as relevant to the campaign 
for the 2000 Democratic presidential nomination. 

</P>
<P>
	Indonesia OKs Return of Timor Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	KUPANG, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia will let the United Nations  
fly refugees home to East Timor from their squalid camps, U.N. 
officials said today, offering hope to more than 100,000 people 
evicted from their homeland. Craig Sanders, who is leading a U.N. 
assessment mission in West Timor, told The Associated Press that 
some refugees could be taken back on U.N.-chartered flights as 
early as Wednesday. Aid agencies say the majority of the 230,000 
refugees taken to West Timor -- many of them against their will -- 
would return if given a chance. 

</P>
<P>
	Austria Far-Right Party Makes Gains  
</P>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- A far-right party whose leader once  
praised the Hitler era made large gains in Austria's general 
elections today, moving into second place, according to preliminary 
results. The results, broadcast by Austrian television gave the 
Freedom Party of Joerg Haider 28.4 percent, a gain of 6.5 
percentage points. That allowed them to overtake the centrist 
People's Party, in second place going into the elections. They had 
27.8 percent, with 33 percent of the votes counted. The Socialists 
remained first, with 32.8 percent. But they lost heavily -- 5.3 
percentage points. 

</P>
<P>
	Radio City Restoration Complete  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After a $70 million restoration, the  
once-neglected Radio City Music Hall is reopening with a 
star-studded gala. From its newly woven 3,000-pound gold silk 
curtain to freshly cleaned Depression-era artwork, hidden for 
decades under layers of grit and grime, the landmark theater has 
been restored to its former Art Deco grandeur. The theater reopens 
tomorrow night with a benefit featuring Billy Crystal, Ann-Margret, 
Sting, Tony Bennett, 98 Degrees, Ann Miller and Raquel Welch. It is 
the first major renovation since the building opened Dec. 27, 1932. 

</P>
<P>
	Serena Williams Wins Grand Slam  
</P>
<P>
	MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- Serena Williams beat older sister Venus  
for the first time in their professional careers today to capture 
the Grand Slam Cup and a $900,000 payday. The U.S. Open champion 
won 6-1, 3-6, 6-3 in a final filled with errors by both players. 
Venus, at 19 one year older, applauded Serena and the sisters 
embraced at the net after the match, but did not show much emotion 
during play. Earlier, Greg Rusedski used his big serve to overpower 
Tommy Haas in four sets in the men's final. Rusedski, a 
Canadian-born Briton, won 6-3, 6-4, 6-7 (5-7), 7-6 (7-5). 

</P>
<P>
	Sapp Sits Out Showdown Vs. Vikings  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Tampa Bay Buccaneers defensive tackle Warren  
Sapp is forced to sit out today's game with the Minnesota Vikings 
because of his broken left hand. ``The doctors said it would be 
better for him to wait for Green Bay'' next week, team spokesman 
Reggie Roberts said. Sapp, the NFC defensive player of the month 
for September, broke two bones in his left hand last week against 
Denver, although he returned to play the second half. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
