<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 11:40:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Koch Brothers Head Back to Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- The latest chapter of the battle between the  
Koch brothers heads to a federal court Monday with allegations that 
Koch Industries, the country's leading crude purchaser, stole oil 
from the Indians and independent producers. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Koch is suing the company his father built and his older  
brother, Charles, now runs. The civil lawsuit claims the company 
based in Wichita, Kan., stole millions of dollars by underreporting 
the amounts of oil purchased from federal leases and Indian lands. 
</P>
<P>
	The Osage Nation, from which Koch gets most of the oil it  
obtains from Indian lands, isn't joining Bill Koch's lawsuit. Chief 
Charles Tillman said the tribe couldn't prove any wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither side will say how much potential liability is faced by  
Koch Industries, the nation's second-largest privately held company 
with $30 billion in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the second time in just over a year that Bill Koch  
(net worth $650 million) has taken his older brother Charles, (net 
worth $3.4 billion), to federal court. Last year in Topeka, Kan., 
Bill Koch unsuccessfully claimed he was cheated out of more than $1 
billion when he sold his stake in Koch Industries back in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Jury selection in the most recent case begins Monday in federal  
court in Tulsa. The trial is expected to last months. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, the lawsuit alleges Koch Industries routinely  
instructed employees to underreport the amount of oil they collect 
from producers' tanks. The lawsuit alleges Koch received 5.3 
million barrels, or more than $133 million, of oil without paying 
for it between 1981 and 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of history behind this case and the parties  
involved,'' said Jay Rosser, spokesman for Koch Industries. ``The 
fact of the matter is that it will be up to a court and a jury to 
evaluate the facts here. And when that's said and done, we're 
confident our integrity will be affirmed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The idea that Oklahoma producers were not aware they were being  
ripped off makes the merits of the Koch case shaky, said Dewey 
Bartlett Jr., president of the Oklahoma Independent Petroleum 
Association. The OIPA represents some 1,200 oil and gas producers 
in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	But according to the American Petroleum Institute's manual on  
standards for measuring crude oil, it is ``impossible'' to measure 
oil without error because of the variables involved. 
</P>
<P>
	The case against Koch Industries is relying in part on company  
records that show millions of dollars in ``overages,'' or the 
amount of oil the company actually took in but did not pay for. 
</P>
<P>
	Koch Industries officials concede the company made about $10  
million in profit per year from the overages. But they say that was 
only a small amount of the company's overall intake. 
</P>
<P>
	``During the time period this suit addresses, Koch purchased and  
transported more than 20 million gallons of crude oil each day,'' 
Rosser said. ``Contrary to the implications of the suit, very, very 
little of that oil came from federal or Native American lands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, several former Koch employees say they were trained  
to alter information on how much oil was collected, according to 
court papers. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillip Dubose, former division manager of Koch Oil Co.'s  
southeastern region, said he was promoted because he changed the 
figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is how you got promoted with Koch,'' Dubose said in an  
interview with The Associated Press. ``They wouldn't use the word 
steal, but they would insinuate to change the numbers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dubose is expected to testify in the Tulsa federal trial. What  
the jury will not hear about is a 1987 U.S. Senate investigation 
that concluded Koch stole oil by deliberate mismeasurement from 
Indian-owned lands in Oklahoma. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge barred the report from the trial because Bill  
Koch was ``involved to some degree'' with the committee's 
investigation, the judge wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	But the FBI agent in charge of the investigation said he never  
talked to Bill Koch during the probe. Jim Elroy said investigators 
set up surveillance on certain Indian leases, including several in 
eastern Oklahoma. Koch employs about 1,000 in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Elroy said they would first observe Koch employees taking gauge  
measurements. Then they would take their own measurements and 
compare figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``We found that they were recording numbers other than the  
numbers they were observing,'' Elroy said. ``When we confronted 
them, they stated that they were trained to do this -- they were 
required to make alterations in the company's favor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elroy currently works for the San Diego law firm that filed the  
lawsuit on behalf of Bill Koch. 
</P>
<P>
	Approximately 85 percent of the oil Koch purchased from Indian  
lands was bought from the Osage Nation in eastern Oklahoma. Chief 
Tillman said they reviewed their records and have not found any 
suspicions of Koch Industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Tillman and others in the oil industry said they will casually  
be paying attention to the trial but do not expect anything more 
than a family fight. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
