<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 17:28:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Talent Infusion Lifts Alabama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- While the program festered in its own  
disillusion and disappointment, Alabama coach Mike DuBose and his 
staff kept hammering away at the only real solution to the 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	They kept recruiting.  
</P>
<P>
	They won commitments, large and small, signing blue-chip  
prospects from the back roads of Mississippi, taking fliers on some 
risky junior-college talent, even coming out on top in a few 
head-to-head recruiting battles against Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	That, as much as luck or fate, was the reason No. 12 Alabama  
pulled one of the major upsets of the year Saturday, defeating the 
No. 8 Gators 40-39 in overtime and ending their 30-game winning 
streak at The Swamp. 
</P>
<P>
	It seems the talent gap between Alabama (4-1, 3-0 Southeastern  
Conference) and Florida (4-1, 2-1) has shrunk since NCAA-imposed 
scholarship reductions during the mid-1990s stripped the Tide of 
numbers and put DuBose in a difficult situation. 
</P>
<P>
	Take, for example, Andrew Zow, the Crimson Tide quarterback who  
came to Alabama from Lake Butler, Fla., only 40 miles up the road 
from Gainesville. A knee injury as a senior in high school made him 
a marginal prospect for the Gators, who envisioned him as a 
defensive back. 
</P>
<P>
	Zow showed them, throwing for 336 yards and two scores in  
possibly the best performance by an Alabama quarterback since Jay 
Barker led the Tide to its last national title in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't play to get back at somebody,'' Zow said. ``I come to  
play for the University of Alabama and my teammates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a high school star in Starkville, Miss., receiver Freddie  
Milons had to choose between Alabama and Florida. He decided to go 
to Alabama, where he could make an immediate impact, instead of 
Florida, where he would have had to wait his turn. 
</P>
<P>
	It seems Milons' instincts were correct. He caught 10 passes for  
119 yards against the Gators to become the first Alabama player to 
surpass 100 yards receiving in consecutive games since Ozzie 
Newsome in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a big game for this program,'' Milons said. ``We beat  
Florida, at home. We ended their 30-game home winning streak. We 
were the major underdog, but we shocked everyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of all, they shocked the Gators.  
</P>
<P>
	Florida had become the power of the SEC after a decade of  
stockpiling talent, much the way Alabama did in the days of Bear 
Bryant. 
</P>
<P>
	If Florida didn't sense Alabama's resurgence before the game, it  
surely did afterwards. 
</P>
<P>
	This was Florida's first loss at home since October 1994, when  
Terry Bowden and Auburn won 36-33 at The Swamp. One big difference: 
the Tigers had beaten Florida the previous year in Auburn. This 
latest loss seemed to take the Gators by surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't see the same fire and intensity as I saw against  
Tennessee,'' Florida defensive lineman Gerard Warren said, 
referring to a 23-21 victory two weeks ago. ``Maybe some guys 
underestimated them and didn't take them as seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the defeat, Florida remains on track for a berth in  
the SEC title game at Atlanta and a possible rematch with the 
Crimson Tide. The Gators still hold the tiebreaker over Tennessee 
and will get to Atlanta by winning the rest of their conference 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Spurrier would like to think his team will learn something  
from its mistakes in a rematch. Three turnovers resulted in 17 
points for Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, the final error: a miss on the extra point in overtime by  
Jeff Chandler. 
</P>
<P>
	It was made all the more painful when Alabama's Chris Kemp  
missed as well, but an offsides penalty gave him a second chance. 
</P>
<P>
	He made it, and DuBose, whose job appeared in jeopardy two weeks  
ago, won his second straight game against a team in the Top 25. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
