<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs Players Lobby for Manager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The last-place Chicago Cubs ended the season  
sticking up for manager Jim Riggleman. 
</P>
<P>
	``The old adage is, Jimmy didn't throw one pitch, he didn't  
throw one ball,'' Mark Grace said Sunday after the Cubs finished 
with a 9-5 loss to the St. Louis Cardinals. ``He was the same guy 
that was runner-up for manager of the year last year. He didn't 
just forget what to do. It's our fault, from Sammy (Sosa) to me to 
the 25th guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs finished 30 games behind division winner Houston at  
67-95 and only Florida, with three fewer victories, was worse. It 
was their poorest showing since 1980, not counting the strike 
shortened seasons in 1994 and 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love what I'm doing, and as much as I love it, I don't think  
anyone could enjoy managing anymore than I do,'' said Riggleman, 
374-419 in five years with the Cubs. ``As I've said many times 
before, it's not the cure for cancer, the way to world peace. There 
are a lot of tough things going on in the world, and whether the 
manager comes back is pretty low on the list of priorities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the second straight game, Cubs general manager Ed Lynch  
chatted with Riggleman in the visitors' clubhouse. In August, Lynch 
tried to quell rumors that Riggleman would be fired by committing 
to the manager though the end of the season. Any evaluation, he 
said, would come after the season ended. 
</P>
<P>
	Both had their contracts extended one year in August 1998 by  
Cubs president Andy MacPhail. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Trachsel, who lost Sunday and finished 8-18, also said  
Riggleman wasn't to blame. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not the reason we had this kind of season,'' Trachsel  
said. ``We have to look at ourselves for the reasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grace left no doubt that he wanted to see Riggleman return.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's going to be a better team next year -- I don't  
think the changes need to be made in the dugout,'' Grace said. 
``They need to be made between the lines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two games into the season, the Cubs were in first place with a  
.500 record. They remained tied for the lead for only three games, 
before falling into third after a 9-3 loss to Pittsburgh on May 10. 
They didn't move above .500 until May 1, 21 games in. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs were one game back of the lead in the NL Central three  
times. But after beating Arizona 5-3 on June 8 to close within one 
for the last time, the Cubs lost 10 of 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa, who closed the year with his 63rd home run, said he would  
like to see Riggleman back in the clubhouse next year. But he said 
the decision wasn't his to make. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love to play with Riggs. He's been a great guy with me,''  
Sosa said. ``But, if something happens from now on, I don't have 
any control over it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
