<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 14:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Looking beyond his tenure in the Oval Office,  
President Clinton wondered aloud about following Ronald Reagan's 
path in reverse. 
</P>
<P>
	``If President Reagan could be an actor and become president,''  
he told a Hollywood crowd gathered at the home of director Rob 
Reiner. ``Maybe I could become an actor. I've got a good pension, I 
can work for cheap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mel Brooks and Carl Reiner had just offered up a 1990s version  
of their 2,000-year-old man routine for Clinton's enjoyment, and 
the president could not resist a few quips of his own. Blame it on 
the long days on the fund-raising trail. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's 2 a.m. on my body clock and I'm reduced to being Gray  
Davis' straight man,'' Clinton said, referring to the famously dull 
California governor who, speaking before Clinton, bragged that Al 
Gore was his ``charisma consultant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton revealed that he was a big fan of the comedy practiced  
by Brooks and Reiner. ``I have a videotape of 'Blazing Saddles' and 
I watch it every six months whether I need to or not,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	And he had an idea for a comeback film for Brooks, creator of  
``The Producers,'' a spoof of Hollywood storytellers that includes 
a production called ``Springtime for Hitler.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``All the Republicans, they've been fighting over what to do  
about Pat Buchanan now that he's got this interesting 
interpretation of World War II,'' Clinton said. ``I suggested that 
Mel might put him in a remake of 'The Producers.' That would be a 
good thing to do with Pat Buchanan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	After a breakfast with friends on Sunday, Clinton stopped by the  
home of film mogul Lew Wasserman, and spent several minutes looking 
over memorabilia in Wasserman's screening room. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the mementos: Wasserman's 1974 Oscar, a photo album from  
Jimmy Stewart's 1949 ``stag party'' and dozens of bound books 
containing photographs Wasserman collected over his long career. 
</P>
<P>
	One picture showed Lou Gehrig checking out the sleeve of Babe  
Ruth's baseball uniform. Another showed a young Bette Davis sitting 
coyly on a grassy slope. There also were framed photos of President 
Lyndon Johnson, and Wasserman hugging Johnson's wife, Lady Bird. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Clinton attended a luncheon fund-raiser that brought  
in $500,000 for Rep. Brad Sherman, D-Calif., at the home of 
businessman Richard Ziman. He was addressing a $250,000 dinner for 
the DNC as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton had a late-night fund-raiser over dessert to benefit the  
Democratic National Committee before a late departure to Washington 
aboard Air Force One to prepare to go head-to-head with Congress 
over the patients' bill of rights and the budget this week. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald Reagan's name kept coming up during Clinton's three-day  
fund-raising swing through Nevada and California. The trip raised 
$2.5 million for Democrats' campaigns in the 2000 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks suggested that he was the greatest actor that ever lived,  
and that he turned in his most stunning performance at the White 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you didn't know any better, you would think he was the  
president,'' he said. ``He fooled Gorbachev!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton invoked the Reagan-Bush years to draw a distinction  
between his economic policies and the GOP, saying ``Mr. Reagan and 
Mr. Bush brought in the supply-side economics, which defied 
arithmetic and quadrupled the debt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I used to have a senior senator (from Arkansas) named Dale  
Bumpers who had a great line about supply-side economics,'' Clinton 
said. ``'If you'll let me write $2 billion worth of hot checks I'll 
show you a good time, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest single event over the weekend was an $850,000 dinner  
Saturday night for House candidates put on by Access Now for Gay 
and Lesbian Equality -- the highlight of which was a lively number 
by the Gay Men's Chorus trumpeting the role of homosexuals in 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	One-liners from the song -- such as ``You can't have New York  
without Queens'' -- tickled the president's fancy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was back there, feverishly trying to write down all those  
lines,'' he told the crowd. ``If someone would furnish me with the 
lyrics of that song, I would be eternally grateful.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
