<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Oct. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	PM's Party Said Leading India Vote  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- A coalition led by Hindu nationalists  
probably won India's parliamentary elections that ended Sunday, 
exit polls predicted. Two exit polls conducted by television 
networks at the end of the world's biggest election said the 
Bharatiya Janata Party, headed by Prime Minister Atal Bihari 
Vajpayee, would return to power with help from 21 parties in its 
campaign alliance. The main rival Congress Party -- led by 
Italian-born Sonia Gandhi, widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv 
Gandhi -- and its allies placed second, but with too few seats to 
form a government. 

</P>
<P>
	29 Chechens Said Killed by Russia  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- A nighttime Russian bombing raid on a  
Chechen town killed 28 civilians, many of them children, residents 
and Chechen officials said today. Russian military officials in the 
neighboring territory of Dagestan refused to comment on the air 
raid. Russia has been bombing Chechnya for the past two weeks and 
has been moving troops several miles inside Chechnya's border in an 
attempt to create a security zone around the rebellious territory. 
Russia began the raids after Muslim militants from Chechnya invaded 
neighboring Dagestan in August and September, seeking to create an 
Islamic state in southern Russia. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Prepared for Tight Race  
</P>
<P>
	DOVER, N.H. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore brought his retooled  
campaign to New Hampshire today, calling himself the underdog in 
the presidential primary race against Bill Bradley. ``The race has 
changed and it's now a two-person race that is close and 
hard-fought,'' Gore told reporters after a closed-door pep talk 
with supporters. Gore repeated his challenge for a series of 
debates with Bradley soon; to wait until January would leave too 
little time before the primaries begin, he said. 

</P>
<P>
	West Bank-Gaza Link Delayed  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- In the first major setback in the revived peace  
process, Israelis said Sunday that only technical issues delay the 
opening of a land link for Palestinians between the West Bank and 
the Gaza Strip. Palestinians insisted issues of principle are at 
stake. The passage is to provide the first unfettered route for 
Palestinians between the two areas. Palestinians say the delay is 
due to Israel's insistence that it issue the passes and maintain 
power of arrest along the route. 

</P>
<P>
	United May Bid for Air Canada  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- United Airlines's parent, UAL Corp., and German  
airline Lufthansa are preparing a bid to buy 35 percent or more of 
the outstanding shares of Air Canada, the Chicago Tribune reported 
in today's editions. The bid, which could come as early as 
tomorrow, could block the merger of Air Canada and Canadian 
Airlines proposed by investment firm Onex Corp. That combination is 
being backed by American Airlines and its parent, AMR Corp. AMR 
owns 25 percent of Canadian Airlines and would own 15 percent of 
the new carrier. 

</P>
<P>
	NYC Art Exhibit Attracts Thousands  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The curious gathered in long lines for a second  
day to see the art exhibit Mayor Rudolph Giuliani found so 
offensive he cut the museum's funding, a decision he defended again 
today. The museum -- which usually gets little notice -- is basking 
in the attention. More than 9,200 people viewed ``Sensation'' 
yesterday, its first day. It was the largest opening in the 
museum's 175-year history. More than 4,000 showed up today, waiting 
in line for up to 90 minutes and paying $9.75 for tickets. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices slipped in early trading Monday.  
The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 25.28 points to 
17,687.28. On Friday, the index climbed 107.10 points, or 0.61 
percent. Friday on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average 
closed at 10,273.00 points, down 63.95. 

</P>
<P>
	49ers Hand Titans Their First Loss  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Looking much like Steve Young, Jeff Garcia  
threw for two touchdowns and ran for another as the 49ers held off 
Tennessee 24-22 today, knocking the Titans from the ranks of the 
unbeaten. It was San Francisco's 19th straight win at home. The 
49ers continued a pattern of success when they've had to play 
without their starting quarterback, improving to 7-1 in eight games 
without Young since 1996 as the backups fit right into San 
Francisco's West Coast offense. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  











  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
