<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Reds Wait, Watch Mets Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- While the New York Mets were saving their  
playoff lives, the Cincinnati Reds could only wait and watch. 
</P>
<P>
	Steady sheets of rain pounded County Stadium in Milwaukee at the  
scheduled 4 p.m. EDT start time of Cincinnati's season finale 
against the Brewers. As of 6:45 p.m., it had been raining steadily 
for six hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Though both teams desperately wanted to finish their seasons on  
time, a foreboding forecast suggested a delay until Monday was 
possible. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds needed to win the game to avert a stunning collapse in  
the season's final weekend. Cincinnati controlled its own playoff 
destiny two days earlier, but consecutive losses to the lowly 
Brewers let the Mets back in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Houston's victory over Los Angeles on Sunday clinched the NL  
Central title for the Astros (97-65). It also meant the Reds 
(95-66) must beat Milwaukee to force a one-game playoff with New 
York (96-66) on Monday at Cinergy Field. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Cincinnati-Milwaukee game was postponed, it was to be  
rescheduled for 2:05 p.m. EDT Monday. And if that occurred and the 
Reds won, there was to be a one-game playoff between New York and 
Cincinnati for the wild-card slot at Cinergy Field on Tuesday at 
2:05 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	In the event the Reds and Mets needed to play Tuesday, Game 1 in  
each NL playoff series would be pushed back a day until Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The best weather forecasts available to the Brewers suggested  
intermittent rains until Monday morning, but there appeared to be a 
window of calm about 8 p.m. EDT when the game might be able to get 
underway. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds, who looked battered when they left the field Saturday  
after their 10-6 loss to the Brewers, watched the Mets-Pirates and 
Dodgers-Astros games on clubhouse televisions. The Brewers showed 
the game on the stadium's video screen for the few thousand fans 
who braved the elements. 
</P>
<P>
	The NL said the Brewers would decide whether to cancel the game.  
Milwaukee sold over 54,000 tickets to the game, which was expected 
to be the last ever played in County Stadium before a July crane 
accident at Miller Park delayed the new stadium's opening for a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Between innings, the video screen flashed the message, ``The  
Weather Situation continues to be monitored. All efforts will be 
made to play today's game. Thank you for your patience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reds manager Jack McKeon ventured into the outfield to test the  
turf about an hour after the game's scheduled start time, and he 
waved when fans in the left-field stands cheered him. 
</P>
<P>
	A few Brewers players wandered out into the steady downpour  
about an hour before the scheduled game time to sign autographs for 
several hundred fans wearing ponchos and slickers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Twins-White Sox game 90 miles south in Chicago finished in a  
1-1 tie called after 6 1/2 innings because of a rain. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991003.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 17:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
