<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 09:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Composites Making Their Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KETTERING, Ohio (AP) -- Researchers working at the National  
Composite Center here are hoping their area will soon get a 
distinctive new name like California's Silicon Valley. They like 
Composite Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Composites, they say, are the material of the future.  
</P>
<P>
	These days, less and less wood and steel are going into doors,  
shingles, golf clubs, utility poles, truck beds and highway 
bridges. 
</P>
<P>
	Materials made of fiber, resins and plastics -- especially  
glass-fiber and carbon-fiber materials -- are being used instead. 
These new materials can be made lighter, sometimes stronger, and 
they don't rust. 
</P>
<P>
	New uses are popping up all the time.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've got a person who wants to build a composite storm  
shelter,'' said Mark Brandt, vice president of the National 
Composite Center's commercial sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Jean Yeager, a senior engineer at the center in this Dayton  
suburb, said composite material is not the ``flash in the pan'' 
some had predicted 10 years ago. ``It is here to stay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At present, it's impossible to say how much composite material  
is produced or sold each year because it is used in such diverse 
products and industries. Its advocates says it can be just as 
strong -- and even cheaper. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Dick's sporting goods store in Dayton stocks a few  
composite fishing rods that sell for $11.99. By contrast, aluminum 
poles cost $99.99, and graphite poles range from in price from 
$19.99 to $89.99. 
</P>
<P>
	How much more the industry grows depends on whether composites  
become accepted in such everyday fixtures as street signs, fences 
and guardrails, and whether they find their way into big-ticket 
items such as military aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Center officials recently announced that they have successfully  
made a tail cone and fighter aircraft panel out of carbon-fiber 
composites. They said the parts can be up to 85 percent chearper 
than composite parts made through conventional processes. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Composite Center was set up with state funding in  
1996 to commercialize composite materials developed at 
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base and expand the region's industrial 
base. 
</P>
<P>
	The private, not-for-profit center was born after economic  
development officials became concerned about the erosion of local 
jobs in the military and auto industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The center recruited scientists from Wright-Patterson who had  
been working on composites for years and then moved them into a 
vacated Defense Department warehouse. State and federal grants 
supply 80 percent of the center's funding; the rest comes from 
clients. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike universities and other groups working on composites, the  
center has the room and equipment to actually develop manufacturing 
processes and produce prototypes, according to its president, Louis 
Luedtke. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials hope that within the next few years the region will  
become known as the largest center for development of composites in 
the country. That's when it will truly be Composite Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	The center, which employs about 25 people, is a modest presence  
today. It's housed in a squat, gray building several blocks long. 
Its centerpiece is a 1,000-ton injection-molding press that stamps 
out molds for composite truck beds. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeager pauses during a tour of the building to jump on top of an  
overturned truck bed with all of her 115 pounds to demonstrate its 
strength. The bed bends but doesn't break. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeager said automakers are interested in the truck bed because  
the federal government is requiring them to increase gas mileage. 
</P>
<P>
	``One way to do that is get weight out of the vehicle,'' she  
said. ``You get the weight out by using composite materials and not 
giving up strength.'' 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors Corp. plans to offer a composite plastic cargo  
bed as an option on its 2001 Chevrolet Silverado full-sized pickup. 
And Ford Motor Co. plans to have a composite bed standard on its 
Explorer Sport Trac that's scheduled to go on sale early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	A designer model ranch house in Cupertino, Calif., features  
composite shingle siding that looks like wood, but won't fade, rot 
and is fire-resistant. An Arizona company says its composite 
utility poles could render the wooden variety virtually extinct. 
</P>
<P>
	In Ohio, the state Legislature recently approved funding to  
build 100 highway bridges with composite decks in the next six 
years. Each of the state's 88 counties will get at least one 
bridge. 
</P>
<P>
	``Composite bridges show the potential for two to three times  
the life of a current cement bridge,'' said Yeager. ``Concrete 
bridges are very susceptible to weather conditions,'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brandt said the center has gotten inquiries from people  
interested in using composites for motorcycle fenders, crash-test 
dummies, inserts for shoes, and even bulletproof vests. 
</P>
<P>
	``They go all over the map,'' he said. ``We try to help them  
figure out how to make it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Glowinski, executive director of the American Wood  
Council, said many composites include wood fibers and that 
woodmakers are using composites to improve their own products. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think our industry will see this as a threat, but an  
opportunity,'' Glowinski said. ``Our industry is well involved in 
the development of composite material.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Jeanes, senior vice president of marketing for the  
American Iron and Steel Institute, said he doesn't see composites 
replacing iron and steel on a widespread basis at this time. But he 
acknowledged that composites are being used in certain areas, such 
as the construction industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Composites is having a presence there, but it seems more  
appropriate to filling in little niche components,'' said Jeanes. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he said the steel industry is interested in how the  
benefits of composites can be applied to steel to make it a better 
product. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991003.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 17:28:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta's Second Ice Age Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Understandably, the Atlanta Thrashers were a bit  
nervous for their first NHL game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were squeezing splinters out of our sticks,'' coach Curt  
Fraser said. ``Once we relax and get more comfortable, we'll be 
fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Thrashers began the city's second ice age Saturday night,  
losing to the New Jersey Devils 4-1, 19 years after the Flames 
played their final game in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The result didn't seem to matter much to the hockey-starved  
crowd of 18,545, at least half of them adorned in white Thrashers 
sweaters. 
</P>
<P>
	They cheered the Zamboni driver. They cheered when the mascot  
swooped in from the ceiling on a cable during loud pregame 
festivities. They cheered when the announcer proclaimed, ``Atlanta, 
you now live in a hockey town.'' They cheered when former Flames 
coach Bernie Geoffrion dropped the ceremonial first puck. They 
cheered when Kelly Buchberger scored the first goal. They cheered 
at the end when the seconds ticked off the clock, even though their 
team had been stymied by Martin Brodeur's goaltending and two goals 
by Bobby Holik. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a good day. A lot of things we planned went off without  
a hitch, except the game,'' general manager Don Waddell said. 
``When the people stood up to cheer with 20 seconds left, that was 
incredible. I think that shows the fans are ready for this and will 
be very supportive of this club.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even from the top row of the new $213 million Philips Arena, the  
view was just fine for Hockey Night in Atlanta, Part II. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm surprised,'' said Ted Charette, sipping on a beer in his  
$10 seat. ``I had heard a lot of talk that there wasn't a bad seat 
in the house. I get to bear witness to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Season-ticket holder Alan Cowart dug deep in his closet and  
pulled out an old Atlanta Flames sweater to wear to the Thrashers 
first game. It didn't fit after 19 years in mothballs, so he passed 
it off to his wife, Cindy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It used to be a great atmosphere at those Flames games,''  
Cowart said. ``We could have the same sort of thing now, but the 
people have got to be patient. They're trying to build from the 
ground up. We've got to give it time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inspired by the raucous crowd, the Thrashers dominated play in  
the first period, outshooting the Devils 15-7. But Brodeur kept it 
scoreless with several outstanding saves, including a stop on Steve 
Staios from in front of the net. 
</P>
<P>
	The Thrashers seemed to burn themselves out in that opening  
period and began making mistakes. The Devils, who had the best 
record in the Eastern Conference last season, capitalized on just 
about every one. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of good things happened,'' said 35-year-old Ray Ferraro,  
one of the few prominent Thrashers on a roster filled with 
nondescript players. ``Unfortunately, a couple of mistakes cost us 
big.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchberger, the Thrashers' captain, scored the first goal in  
team history at 11:26 of the second period. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrik Stefan, the top overall pick in the entry draft, fed a  
pass to Buchberger, who blasted a shot past Brodeur's glove as the 
goalie came sliding across the crease. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an honor, no question,'' said Buchberger, whose goal cut  
the Devils' lead to 2-1. ``It would have been nicer if we had won 
the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any hope of a comeback faded at 6:31 of the third when Sergei  
Brylin restored a two-goal lead for the Devils. About six minutes 
later, Holik ended the scoring with his second goal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a good learning experience for us,'' Fraser said. ``We  
can build off this.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
