<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta's Second Ice Age Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Understandably, the Atlanta Thrashers were a bit  
nervous for their first NHL game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were squeezing splinters out of our sticks,'' coach Curt  
Fraser said. ``Once we relax and get more comfortable, we'll be 
fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Thrashers began the city's second ice age Saturday night,  
losing to the New Jersey Devils 4-1, 19 years after the Flames 
played their final game in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The result didn't seem to matter much to the hockey-starved  
crowd of 18,545, at least half of them adorned in white Thrashers 
sweaters. 
</P>
<P>
	They cheered the Zamboni driver. They cheered when the mascot  
swooped in from the ceiling on a cable during loud pregame 
festivities. They cheered when the announcer proclaimed, ``Atlanta, 
you now live in a hockey town.'' They cheered when former Flames 
coach Bernie Geoffrion dropped the ceremonial first puck. They 
cheered when Kelly Buchberger scored the first goal. They cheered 
at the end when the seconds ticked off the clock, even though their 
team had been stymied by Martin Brodeur's goaltending and two goals 
by Bobby Holik. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a good day. A lot of things we planned went off without  
a hitch, except the game,'' general manager Don Waddell said. 
``When the people stood up to cheer with 20 seconds left, that was 
incredible. I think that shows the fans are ready for this and will 
be very supportive of this club.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even from the top row of the new $213 million Philips Arena, the  
view was just fine for Hockey Night in Atlanta, Part II. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm surprised,'' said Ted Charette, sipping on a beer in his  
$10 seat. ``I had heard a lot of talk that there wasn't a bad seat 
in the house. I get to bear witness to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Season-ticket holder Alan Cowart dug deep in his closet and  
pulled out an old Atlanta Flames sweater to wear to the Thrashers 
first game. It didn't fit after 19 years in mothballs, so he passed 
it off to his wife, Cindy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It used to be a great atmosphere at those Flames games,''  
Cowart said. ``We could have the same sort of thing now, but the 
people have got to be patient. They're trying to build from the 
ground up. We've got to give it time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inspired by the raucous crowd, the Thrashers dominated play in  
the first period, outshooting the Devils 15-7. But Brodeur kept it 
scoreless with several outstanding saves, including a stop on Steve 
Staios from in front of the net. 
</P>
<P>
	The Thrashers seemed to burn themselves out in that opening  
period and began making mistakes. The Devils, who had the best 
record in the Eastern Conference last season, capitalized on just 
about every one. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of good things happened,'' said 35-year-old Ray Ferraro,  
one of the few prominent Thrashers on a roster filled with 
nondescript players. ``Unfortunately, a couple of mistakes cost us 
big.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchberger, the Thrashers' captain, scored the first goal in  
team history at 11:26 of the second period. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrik Stefan, the top overall pick in the entry draft, fed a  
pass to Buchberger, who blasted a shot past Brodeur's glove as the 
goalie came sliding across the crease. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an honor, no question,'' said Buchberger, whose goal cut  
the Devils' lead to 2-1. ``It would have been nicer if we had won 
the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any hope of a comeback faded at 6:31 of the third when Sergei  
Brylin restored a two-goal lead for the Devils. About six minutes 
later, Holik ended the scoring with his second goal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a good learning experience for us,'' Fraser said. ``We  
can build off this.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
