<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of Japan Sees Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- In some good news for Japan's economy, the central  
bank said Monday that business confidence at major manufacturing 
companies improved sharply during the past three months. 
</P>
<P>
	In its closely-watched quarterly ``tankan'' survey, the Bank of  
Japan said sentiment among large manufacturers had brightened over 
the last survey to a figure of minus 22 from minus 37, it's biggest 
improvement since November 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	The tankan measures the percentage of firms seeing business  
conditions improve minus the percentage seeing conditions worsen. 
The bank surveyed 9,275 companies in September for the latest 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	The result exceeded analysts' expectations. Economists surveyed  
by the Dow Jones Newswires had forecast the index for large 
manufacturers would come to a minus 27 in the latest survey. 
</P>
<P>
	And large manufacturers are also optimistic that conditions will  
improve by the time of the next survey. They see sentiment 
advancing to a figure of minus 16 by December. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentiment also improved in all categories of company surveyed,  
from big non-manufacturers to small manufacturers. And all see 
further improvement by December. 
</P>
<P>
	The improved sentiment comes on the heels of two straight  
quarters of growth in Japan's economy and a drop in the jobless 
rate from a record high. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's gross domestic product -- the measure of all goods and  
services produced within its borders -- expanded 2.0 percent for the 
first quarter of the year after more than a year of recession. It 
followed that up with a gain of 0.2 percent in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the government announced that the unemployment rate  
fell to 4.7 percent in August from a record high of 4.9 percent the 
previous month. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's economy has been struggling to emerge from its deepest  
downturn in a half century. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading, the yen strengthened on the results of the  
tankan report. The U.S. dollar was quoted at 104.64 yen, down 1.30 
yen from late Friday in Tokyo. Tokyo stocks moved slightly lower on 
fears of a stronger yen, falling 0.14 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities fear that if the yen becomes too strong the  
country's budding economic recovery could be endangered as profits 
at big exporters suffer. A stronger yen makes Japanese products 
more expensive in overseas markets. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
