<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Walker Wins Batting Title Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Larry Walker won his second straight National  
League batting title Sunday, but he wasn't in much of a mood to 
celebrate. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Walker's major league-leading .379 average, the Colorado  
Rockies finished last for the first time in their seven-year 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good thing, I guess,'' Walker said of his  
accomplishment. ``In the same breath, it's a bad thing. It's all 
right to have a batting title then keep playing, but to win the 
batting title and go home, it doesn't mean as much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walker, who had season-ending knee surgery Thursday, finished 43  
points ahead of Arizona outfielder Luis Gonzalez. Boston's Nomar 
Garciaparra hit .357 to win the AL batting crown. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker's margin of victory was the largest for an NL batting  
champion since Stan Musial of St. Louis hit .376 to finish 43 
points ahead of Philadelphia's Richie Ashburn in 1948. 
</P>
<P>
	Bothered by elbow problems early in the season and knee problems  
late, Walker put up impressive numbers in 127 starts. He hit 37 
home runs with 115 RBIs, 108 runs scored and 11 stolen bases. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the most part, I was out there and able to do most of the  
things I am capable of doing, whether it was running the bases or 
chasing down balls,'' Walker said. ``I was hurt to the effect I 
didn't make myself look bad out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His home numbers were straight out of a video game; he hit .461  
with 26 homers and 70 RBIs in 66 games at Coors Field, compared to 
a modest .286 average with 11 home runs and 45 RBIs in 61 road 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker took control of the batting race during a three-game  
series against Philadelphia in late August. Phillies outfielder 
Bobby Abreu trailed Walker by seven points (.357 to .350) entering 
the weekend but trailed by 14 when it was over. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had those situations last year when Tony Gwynn came to town,  
and the year before when we had to battle with him head-to-head,'' 
Walker said. ``It helps to have them right there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hitting .366 after the Philadelphia series, Walker hit .513  
(20-for-39) in September to raise his average 13 more points before 
having surgery to repair cartilage in his left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	He is expected to return by the start of spring training  
</P>
<P>
	Walker hit .363 to win his first batting crown last year and  
finished at .366 when he was the National League MVP in 1997. He is 
first player to hit .360 or better in three consecutive seasons 
since Hall of Fame outfielder Al Simmons did it for the 
Philadelphia A's from 1929-31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
