<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Lose Home Field Opportunity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- With three straight losses to Toronto,  
Cleveland lost its chance for 100 wins and home-field advantage 
throughout the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say we had a very good season, considering all we had  
to go through,'' Indians manager Mike Hargrove said after Sunday's 
9-2 defeat. ``We'll see what we can do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seeking its first World Series title since 1948, the Indians  
open the best-of-5 first round Wednesday at home against Boston. If 
they advance to the league championship series, they would have the 
home-field advantage against Texas but not against New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove isn't yet saying who will start the opener against  
Pedro Martinez (23-4), but it's likely to be Bartolo Colon (18-5). 
</P>
<P>
	``Boston is dangerous in a five-game series,'' Cleveland's  
Travis Fryman said. ``They are well managed, have a great, great 
pitcher and have had to overcome hurdles to get here. They are 
going to be tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fryman and catcher Sandy Alomar Jr., two key Cleveland starters,  
tested injured knees the final weeks of the season, and both said 
Sunday they feel ready now. 
</P>
<P>
	``Game 1 is always important. If you can knock out their best  
pitcher right away, you can relax more,'' Alomar said. ``We want to 
go out and minimize our mistakes. Every mistake in the postseason 
is huge. Hopefully, we can control that, win three games and move 
on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians beat Boston 3-1 in the first round last year, then  
lost to the Yankees 4-2. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like we have to play Boston every year,'' Alomar  
said. ``The bottom line is we just have to go out and play good 
baseball.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
