<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phoenix Said in Good Financial Shape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Despite a drop in ticket revenues and an increase  
in player salaries, analysts say the Arizona Diamondbacks are 
financially sound. 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks earned $21.1 million from baseball operations,  
but reported a $30.3 million net loss related to writeoffs of 
player salaries for the year that ended Dec. 31, The Arizona 
Republic reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The next couple of years will tell the tale,'' said Randy  
Vataha, president of Game Plan LLC, a Boston investment banking 
firm that specializes in professional sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``But the simplest way to look at it is if you throw out the  
depreciation and amortization, they made about a $15 million net 
profit, so it looks pretty good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Jerry Colangelo, the Diamondbacks' managing general  
partner, called on the team's limited partners to ease a cash 
crunch the team blamed on dwindling attendance, including a 
9,000-seat falloff in season ticket sales and skyrocketing player 
contracts. He sought $24 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the team's 1998 financial statement, however, analysts  
said the cash call did not signify a deep-rooted problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``Baseball is a business of seasonal cash flows,'' said Andrew  
Zimbalist, a professor at Smith College in Northampton, Mass., who 
is an expert in the economics of professional sports. 
</P>
<P>
	Phoenix Newspapers Inc., the parent company of The Republic, is  
a limited partner in the Diamondbacks and increased its investment 
during the recent cash call from $6 million to $7 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
