<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Dr. Death' Begins Trial in SAfrica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- A physician dubbed ``Dr.  
Death'' by the media goes on trial Monday, when prosecutors start 
unpeeling layers of mad chemistry, killings, drug dealing and fraud 
surrounding the apartheid era's chemical and biological warfare 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Wouter Basson -- a heart surgeon who continues in private  
practice -- faces charges that he killed 16 people, supplied poison 
to kill 200 and defrauded the white minority government of more 
than $13 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Details of Basson's secret program began emerging in 1992. Other  
governments -- including the United States, Britain and Switzerland 
-- apparently knew about the program. 
</P>
<P>
	The 274-page indictment said Basson supplied muscle relaxants --  
which caused victims to suffocate by paralyzing their lungs -- to 
clandestine forces set up to eliminate the apartheid state's 
enemies. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those Basson is accused of killing were five unidentified  
men who were tied to trees and smeared with a jelly-like ointment 
that was meant to kill them. When the men didn't die, they were 
injected with an overdose of the muscle relaxants, the indictment 
alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	Bodies of victims were often thrown into the ocean from  
airplanes. 
</P>
<P>
	Basson also allegedly supplied substances used in the early  
1980s to kill more than 200 members of a rebel group that fought 
South African rule in Namibia. Because those killings occurred 
outside South Africa, Basson could only be charged with conspiracy 
to commit murder. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges include Basson's arrest in 1997 for possessing 1,000  
tablets of the popular drug Ecstasy, part of more than 1,900 pounds 
of it produced at government expense and privately sold by the 
physician. 
</P>
<P>
	In testimony last year before the Truth and Reconciliation  
Commission, one scientist described how Basson set up a military 
front company to produce cigarettes laced with anthrax, 
poison-laced chocolate and whiskey, and sugar containing 
salmonella. The intended victims included former President Nelson 
Mandela, shortly after he was released from 27 years in prison in 
1990. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was an extensive project and very good work was done in  
this project,'' Basson told the panel. He did not apply for amnesty 
and refused to answer many questions because of the pending trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States and Britain tried to keep Mandela's  
soon-to-be-elected government from obtaining the chemicals and 
asked the white rulers to destroy them before the first all-race 
vote in 1994, the panel heard. 
</P>
<P>
	Swiss federal prosecutors announced last month that they were  
probing charges of espionage and illegal export of materials and 
technology to the program. 
</P>
<P>
	Basson, who has continued to work for the Defense Department,  
was recently suspended pending the outcome of the trial, said Col. 
John Rohlth, a defense spokesman. His legal costs will be paid by 
the government, the Sunday Independent newspaper reported in 
Johannesburg. 
</P>
<P>
	South African prosecutors investigated the case for two years,  
and expect the trial to last at least 18 months. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
