<HEADLINE> Ravens OT Ogden Leaves on Stretcher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Baltimore Ravens offensive tackle Jonathan Ogden  
was carried off the field on a stretcher with a neck injury after 
diving into a pile for a loose ball Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ogden sustained a severe neck burn but had full motion in his  
arms and legs, the team said. He was taken to a hospital for 
X-rays. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-8, 315-pound Ogden was injured at the end of the  
first half in the game against the Atlanta Falcons. A bad snap in 
the shotgun formation sent quarterback Stoney Case scurrying for 
the ball at the Baltimore 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Case recovered, but Ogden rolled over a pile of players and  
landed on top of Falcons lineman Lester Archambeau. It also 
appeared that Ogden may have taken a blow to the head from another 
Atlanta player. 
</P>
<P>
	While medical officials cared for Ogden, his teammates huddled  
on the sideline in prayer. He was strapped to a backboard, his neck 
stabilized, before being placed on the stretcher. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the half, the Falcons lost quarterback Tony Graziani,  
who sustained a concussion on a hit by Ray Lewis. Graziani was not 
expected to return. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
