<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Recalls Environmentalist Dad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARABOO, Wis. (AP) -- The daughter of environmentalist Aldo  
Leopold still lives in a house built with trees she planted with 
her father on the property where he wrote ``A Sand County Almanac'' 
50 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Father gave us a sense of wonder that has been with us for a  
lifetime,'' Nina Leopold Bradley told The Janesville Gazette in a 
recent interview. 
</P>
<P>
	She is 82 now, a botanist who lives down the road from the  
chicken coop where the Leopold family stayed on weekends when they 
visited the 80-acre property in southern Wisconsin. The federal 
government wants to turn a nearby tract into a wildlife refuge 
named after Leopold. 
</P>
<P>
	The chicken coop that became the family's home is on the  
National Register of Historic Places. 
</P>
<P>
	Just like her father did up until his death in 1948, Leopold  
Bradley takes time to record the natural events of the preserve: 
the last hummingbird of fall, the first junco to arrive in winter, 
the first pasqueflower to bloom in spring. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
