<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Necaxa 2, Alajuela 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Necaxa of Mexico scored two second-half goals,  
including the game-winner while shorthanded, and beat Alajuela of 
Costa Rica 2-1 Sunday night to win the CONCACAF Champions Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory makes Necaxa CONCACAF's representative at the FIFA  
Club World Championships at Brazil in January. 
</P>
<P>
	In the third-place game, Major League Soccer's D.C. United and  
Chicago Fire played to a 2-2 tie. CONCACAF rules state that if the 
third-place game ends in a tie, there is no penalty kick shootout. 
</P>
<P>
	Sergio Vazquez scored the tournament-winning goal for Necaxa in  
the 66th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Necaxa's Agustin Delgado dribbled up the left side and centered  
a ball that Alajuela goalkeeper Alvaro Mesen and Edgar David Oliva 
of Necaxa got to at the same time. The ball bounced in front of the 
goal and left Vazquez with a wide open net. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why did we win? Because we have a great spirit and great  
competitive atmosphere in the team. We have 11 players on the field 
who never give up and always keep fighting,'' Necaxa coach Raul 
Arias Rosas said. ``We gave away the lead but never quit and earned 
the win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alajuela took a 1-0 lead in the 35th minute when Josef Miso was  
tripped inside the penalty box by Necaxa's Salvador Cabrera. Miso 
was awarded a penalty kick and beat Necaxa goalkeeper Hugo Pineda 
to the lower left of the goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Pineda got his revenge on Miso in the 59th minute when he  
stopped a penalty kick off the foot of Miso. Miso was again tripped 
inside the penalty box and had a chance to give Alajuela a 2-1 lead 
but Pineda made a diving one-handed save. 
</P>
<P>
	Necaxa played the final 34 minutes down a man after German Villa  
was ejected for punching Alajuela's Wilmer Lopez. 
</P>
<P>
	Necaxa tied the game two minutes into the second half when Oliva  
made a precise pass to Alex Aguinaga who scissor-kicked the ball 
past a surprised Mesen. 
</P>
<P>
	Aguinaga was named MVP of the tournament.  
</P>
<P>
	The third-place game saw United score in the second minute on  
the way to a 2-0 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	A.J. Wood scored the early goal, taking a short pass from Chris  
Albright, controlled it with his right foot and beat Chicago 
goalkeeper Greg Sutton. 
</P>
<P>
	United made it 2-0 in the 50th minute when Antonio Otero  
out-fought Sutton for the ball just outside the net and kicked in a 
loose ball for the score. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago tied it with two goals in a 9-minute span.  
</P>
<P>
	Ante Razov scored on a free kick from 23 yards out in the 71st  
minute, and Jesse Marsch scored in the 80th minute. Paul Dougherty 
passed the ball to Marsch who dribbled up the left side and beat 
United goalkeeper Mark Simpson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
