<DOCNO> APW19991003.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 12:23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pope Declares Six More Blessed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VATICAN CITY (AP) -- Pope John Paul II put three priests and  
three monks on the road to possible sainthood Sunday, adding to the 
record number of Catholics he has declared blessed during his 
papacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Beatifying five Italians and a Belgian during a ceremony in St.  
Peter's Square, John Paul raised to 938 the number of faithful to 
whom he has accorded that honor since he became pope in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	The pontiff, who has declared 284 Catholics to be saints, is  
intent on singling out exemplary Catholics of the past as models 
for the faithful as the Church moves toward its third millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	John Paul, 79, who has often tired in long ceremonies recently,  
held up fairly well throughout Sunday's beatification, which lasted 
more than two hours. At the end of the ceremony, he waved his hand 
in blessing as he was driven in an open-topped vehicle around the 
tens of thousands of people in the square. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's beatification ceremony, marking the last formal step  
before possible sainthood for the six honored, was the last one 
scheduled before the Church celebrates 2000 as a Holy Year. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those beatified Sunday was Edward Poppe, a Belgian who  
died in 1924 and whom the pope called a model for fellow priests. 
Also beatified were two priests who founded orders of nuns, 
Ferdinando Maria Baccilieri, who died in 1893, and Arcangelo 
Tadini, who died in 1912. 
</P>
<P>
	The three monks honored were Mariano Da Roccacasale, who died in  
1866, and two monks who worked in this century, Diego Oddi and 
Nicola Da Gesturi. John Paul praised them for their spirituality 
and simplicity. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
