<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: NatWest Planning Breakup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- National Westminster Bank is drawing up plans for  
a radical breakup in an effort to stave off the hostile takeover 
bid by the Bank of Scotland, a published report said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank's advisers, J.P. Morgan and Dresdner Kleinwort Benson,  
were drawing up preliminary plans for a disposal program and a 
capital reduction that would enable NatWest to hand back up to $8 
billion to shareholders but leave the core retail and commercial 
bank intact, The Sunday Telegraph said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, NatWest was seeking a ``white knight'' to scuttle the  
takeover bid by the much smaller Bank of Scotland, but it appears 
to have changed course. 
</P>
<P>
	The new strategy, the newspaper said, is to show NatWest is  
worth at least $24 share, compared with the $20.22 a share value of 
the Bank of Scotland offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, bank chairman, Sir David Rowland, has begun an urgent  
search for a heavyweight recruit to take charge of the bank's 
retail operations and restore investor confidence in NatWest's 
management, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Advisers have drawn up a list of potential businesses to be  
disposed of, including Ulster Bank, Gartmore, the fund manager, and 
Greenwich NatWest, the structured finance and capital markets 
business, The Sunday Telegraph said. Those properties reportedly 
could fetch as much as $5.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, NatWest also may look to raise money from its  
property portfolio, including its huge branch network, the 
newspaper said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
