<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 17:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Ponders Impact of Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FALUN, Sweden (AP) -- Volvo is owned by Ford. Stora has merged  
with a Finnish competitor. Ericsson is threatening to pack up and 
move out. 
</P>
<P>
	Globalization is sweeping over Sweden's business flagships, and  
unsettling the people of this small, industrious nation. Swedes are 
questioning their competitive edge and many are worrying about what 
it might mean for their generous cradle-to-grave welfare state. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is very unfortunate for Sweden,'' said Per Westerberg,  
chairman of parliament's industry committee. ``If Sweden is to make 
it, we'll have to be competitive when it comes to taxes and rules, 
education and infrastructure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's a dilemma. Many fear the high taxes and tariffs that pay  
for social programs and give Sweden an enviable living standard 
could become a threat to that very prosperity. 
</P>
<P>
	LM Ericsson, a global telecommunications giant, has moved much  
of its key management abroad, and warns that the whole company may 
leave unless the business climate improves. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, competitive needs have forced other Swedish  
corporations to join forces with outsiders. 
</P>
<P>
	Volvo, often seen abroad as a synonym for Swedish solidity, was  
taken over by Ford this year. The Stora forestry products company, 
one of the world's oldest businesses, merged with Finland's Enso. 
The tradition-steeped Orrefors crystal concern now belongs to 
Danish Royal Copenhagen. 
</P>
<P>
	If the trend continues, the 8.8 million Swedes could see their  
industrial prowess eroded because of diminished clout in 
decision-making and lost jobs for subcontractors, said H.G. 
Wessberg at the Swedish Federation of Industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Worse, he said, is the risk of losing research and development  
programs that keep Sweden on the leading edge of technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Not all Swedes see gloom in globalization. They say foreign  
ownership and investment are an economic boost. 
</P>
<P>
	Outsiders are looking to Sweden, with its political stability,  
efficiency and a highly educated work force. The Swedish economy is 
booming, due in part to its unusually high concentration of 
multinational businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1990 to 1996, direct foreign investment in Sweden, which  
includes buyouts and new businesses, more than doubled, said Peter 
Akinder, adviser to Industry Minister Bjoern Rosengren. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year alone, foreign companies invested $18 billion in  
Sweden, and Swedish companies invested about as much abroad, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had an explosion. This year, we'll likely set a  
record,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	During the past five years, the number of foreign-owned  
companies in Sweden, which joined the European Union in 1995, 
increased by 1,200. Now, 334,000 Swedes work for foreign companies, 
an increase of 120,000 over the same period, according to the 
government statistics agency, SCB. 
</P>
<P>
	The trend is good for Sweden, Akinder argues. ``It has brought  
the business sector competence, capital and more efficient 
leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But some companies are leaving, especially because of a double  
tax on stock dividends. Swedish companies are taxed for all profits 
-- including those paid out in dividends -- and then shareholders are 
taxed for the same dividends. 
</P>
<P>
	That tax was a factor in the decision by the big Swedish bank  
Nordbanken to merge with Finnish Merita. MeritaNordbanken, one of 
northern Europe's major banking groups, is now registered in 
Finland. 
</P>
<P>
	It was also the main reason that the merged StoraEnso forestry  
products company is registered in Finland, said Bjoern Haegglund, 
the group's deputy chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``This merger has put us in a solid, strong position,'' he said.  
``If the international competition gets tougher, it's clear you 
have to get sharper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ann-Christine Strandell, senior economist at Nutek, Sweden's  
national board for industrial and technical development, said more 
companies are reacting to international market forces, without 
regard to Swedish political interests. 
</P>
<P>
	In such places as Falun, a town in central Sweden where Stora  
was a cornerstone for seven centuries, such cold business moves are 
met with disappointment. 
</P>
<P>
	Falun long dreamed of playing host to the Winter Olympics,  
counting on Stora for backing. Now the company headquarters and the 
dream are gone. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people are a bit bitter about the sale,'' said Ruth  
Trued, a real estate agent. 
</P>
<P>
	The copper mine where Stora was founded centuries ago is now a  
tourist attraction, with an adjacent museum. The museum director, 
Tommy Forss, said he understood the merger. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it's sad that the cradle for the world's oldest business  
no longer is the hub around which the operations are centered,'' he 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991003.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 10:35:30 </DATE_TIME>
