<HEADLINE> 2 Kenyans Win Half-Marathon Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALERMO, Sicily (AP) -- Paul Tergat overcame a collision and used  
a strong kick to pass Hendrick Ramaala in the final stages to win 
the World Half-Marathon Championship for the first time Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tergat, a five-time world cross country world champion, nearly  
lost the race in the closing yards when he bumped into a race 
official who went on the course to point the Kenyan toward the 
finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Tergat was timed in 1 hour, 1 minute, 50 seconds, for the 13.1  
miles. South Africa's Ramaala, who led until 100 yards remained, 
had the same time. 
</P>
<P>
	Tesfaye Jifar of Ethiopia was third, a second back.  
</P>
<P>
	Tegla Loroupe, also of Kenya, won her third straight women's  
title. 
</P>
<P>
	Loroupe, who broke her world record for the marathon last  
weekend at Berlin, led all the way, finishing at 1:08:48. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's Mizuki Noguchi was second at 1:09:12, followed by  
Catherine Ndereba of Kenya at 1:09:23. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramaala's second-place finish led South Africa to the men's team  
title. Kenya won the women's title. The United States finished 10th 
in both the men's and women's team scoring. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
