<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ariz. Announces First 3 Starters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Randy Johnson, Todd Stottlemyre and Omar Daal  
will start the first three games of the playoffs for Arizona, and 
Brian Anderson is looking more and more like the probable starter 
if there is a Game 4. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Buck Showalter also decided Sunday on but one of the  
non-pitchers who will be on the 25-man roster. Among those left off 
was first baseman Travis Lee. 
</P>
<P>
	The left-handed Johnson (17-9), the major league strikeout  
leader and NL leader in ERA, will start Tuesday's opener against 
New York or Houston. Stottlemyre (6-3) will go in Wednesday's Game 
2 and the lefty Daal (16-9) will start Game 3 on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	Showalter said he will announce Monday whether Anderson (8-2) or  
Andy Benes (13-12) will be the fourth starter. Anderson started 
Sunday's regular-season finale against San Diego and seemed the 
most likely choice after throwing five shutout innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than Johnson, Anderson has been Arizona's top pitcher down  
the stretch. He's 6-0 in his last nine starts. In one of the 
no-decisions during that stretch, against Pittsburgh on Sept. 14, 
he allowed one hit in seven innings. On Sunday, he gave up three 
hits in five innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd love to start, but at the same time if I'm going to  
relieve, start, whatever, the bottom line is get the next hitter 
out in whatever role it's going to be,'' Anderson said. ``It's 
something that's completely out of my control. All I can do is 
control what I do on the field and if that's good enough to start, 
awesome. If it's not, awesome. I'll go in the bullpen and do the 
best I can there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Showalter will wait until Monday to decide whether catcher  
Damian Miller will be on the roster. Miller, who has a hairline 
fracture in his right wrist, did some throwing and swung the bat 
before Sunday's game. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Miller said his wrist felt good.  
</P>
<P>
	``Even if he feels great today, you've still got to wait until  
tomorrow to see how it is,'' Showalter said. 
</P>
<P>
	If Miller can't go, the roster spot would go to catcher Rod  
Barajas, who played all but the last few weeks with Double-A El 
Paso. 
</P>
<P>
	Showalter will use 11 pitchers and 14 position players. He said  
the last two pitching spots will be filled from among Benes, Darren 
Holmes and Armando Reynoso. 
</P>
<P>
	The reserves among the position players are shortstop Andy Fox,  
outfielder Bernard Gilkey, utility player Lenny Harris, first 
baseman Greg Colbrunn and outfielder Turner Ward. 
</P>
<P>
	The relief pitchers assured roster spots are closer Matt Mantei,  
Gregg Olson, Dan Plesac, Greg Swindell and Bobby Chouinard. 
</P>
<P>
	Showalter said he left off Lee largely because the first baseman  
has yet to fully recover from a severely sprained left ankle. Lee, 
the starter for much of the season, was in a 3-for-43 slump at the 
time he was injured Aug. 15 and had lost his job to rookie Erubiel 
Durazo. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee said he understood but still was disappointed.  
</P>
<P>
	``You're here all year long and it comes to crunch time and you  
get let go,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Showalter said it made more sense to go with Ward, signed after  
Pittsburgh released him in late August. Ward initially signed with 
Arizona's Triple-A team and joined the Diamondbacks Sept. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a healthy player, can play all three outfield positions  
and he's a switch-hitter,'' Showalter said. ``He's done well in his 
short time here, and he's a little better equipped to pinch hit 
physically and experience-wise right now than Travis. If Travis was 
a healthy player, I don't think we'd be having this conversation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The eight starters are third baseman Matt Williams, second  
baseman Jay Bell, Durazo at first, catcher Kelly Stinnett, 
shortstop Hanley Frias, right fielder Tony Womack, center fielder 
Steve Finley and right fielder Luis Gonzalez. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
