<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weather May Trim Pumpkin Crop / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Call it Mother Nature's idea of trick or  
treat. 
</P>
<P>
	Blaming the dry, hot summer weather, Texas Agriculture  
Commissioner Susan Combs says the state's pumpkin crop could be 
smaller than normal. 
</P>
<P>
	Production estimates are down 25 percent to 30 percent in some  
Texas fields, and some fields that were planted early had to be 
replanted because of hail and wind damage. Those may be late in 
maturing, with pumpkins not reaching full color. 
</P>
<P>
	About 95 percent of the state's pumpkin crop is sold for  
jack-o'-lanterns and other Halloween decorations. The best 
jack-o'-lantern pumpkins weigh between 15 pounds and 30 pounds, 
have bright orange rinds and well-defined ribbing. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar pumpkins, weighing two to five pounds with sweeter and  
more tender meat, are favored by consumers for pumpkin pies, the 
state Agriculture Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said pumpkin pie lovers also might want to try a  
white pumpkin, which has a pale orange interior and is more 
flavorful and less stringy than traditional orange varieties. Those 
can be found at farmers' markets and garden centers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Texas pumpkins are a sure sign fall has arrived,'' Ms. Combs  
said last week. ``But to make sure this year is a 'treat' instead 
of a 'trick,' be sure to shop early to get your pick of the 
harvest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Ohio's Catholic bishops, noting the  
beating that farmers have been taking from the weather and low 
commodity prices, issued a plea for prayer and promised increased 
lobbying on behalf of the state's rural communities. 
</P>
<P>
	``In these perilous times, we encourage ongoing public support  
for the hardworking and caring individuals who derive their income 
from the land,'' the bishop's wrote in a letter sent to parish 
leaders last week. 
</P>
<P>
	A report last year raised the bishops' concerns about the  
growing concentration and industrialization of agriculture in Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody thinks about where food comes from or what happens to  
farmers,'' said Jim Tobin, associate director of the Catholic 
Conference of Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	The conference, which represents the six Roman Catholic dioceses  
as well as the Byzantine, Romanian and Ukrainian Catholic churches 
in Ohio, pledged to seek solutions to problems facing farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	The bishops commended Gov. Bob Taft for his $5 million proposal  
last month to help farmers hurt by the drought to look for new 
sources of water and buy hay to get them through the winter. 
</P>
<P>
	But they also urged state and federal officials to do more.  
</P>
<P>
	``Additional state and federal resources should be made  
available to help compensate for crop and livestock losses, as well 
as provide for emergency feeding needs, water assistance and tax 
relief,'' the bishops wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``Issues of commodity pricing, labor compensation, farmland  
preservation, environmental safety and retooling and marketing 
assistance for small and moderate-size farmers should also be 
explored.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, the church would like to act as an intermediary,  
Tobin said. For example, church workers could act as go-betweens 
for farm operators and migrant workers in disputes over health, 
safety, housing and wages. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have the answers, but there really needs to be some  
serious dialogue,'' Tobin said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
