<P>
	``I'll slowly start a general exercise program. Then I'll pick  
up a bat and a baseball, I would assume, maybe Dec. 1 or late 
November.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, speaking publicly for the first time since the  
procedure, said his decision was made with his offseason 
rehabilitation regimen in mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not too far off my regular schedule,'' the third  
baseman said. ``I have a full offseason to recover.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By opting for surgery 11 days before the end of the season,  
Ripken temporarily halted his pursuit of 3,000 hits. He is nine 
hits shy of that plateau. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken hit his 400th home run Sept. 2 and batted a career-high  
.340 in 86 games. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a great year and it was a discouraging year,'' said  
Ripken. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken's father, Cal Sr., died late in spring training. Later,  
the Orioles star went on the disabled list for the first two times 
in his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mentally, it was uplifting and also the worst,'' he added. ``I  
rediscovered a swing I hadn't had. ... I'd like to what would have 
happened if I had that swing over 650 at-bats.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken left the Orioles after experiencing pain in his back  
Sept. 21 in Texas and traveled the next day to Cleveland, where Dr. 
Henry Bohlman performed the 2 1/2-hour procedure after Ripken briefly 
deliberated his options. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe I've been worn down. ... The fact that I'm walking  
around and feeling good are good indicators. I don't have a fear of 
trying it again. The only way you find out is to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While his pain may be subsiding, Ripken has maintained a sense  
of humor through his ordeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want to see the scar?'' he asked reporters, pulling up his  
black warmup jersey to reveal a six-inch scar on the middle of his 
lower back, just above his waistline. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
