<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 13:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China To Deregulate Silver Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- In preparation for eventually loosening controls  
on its gold market, China plans to deregulate its silver market by 
the beginning of next year, the official newspaper China Daily's 
Business Weekly reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The central government has always banned free trading in gold,  
silver and other precious metals, keeping it under the control of 
the country's de facto central bank, the People's Bank of China. 
</P>
<P>
	Controls on silver trading will be lifted gradually, with just a  
few domestic traders allowed access once a nonferrous metals 
wholesale market opens for business in Shanghai on Jan. 1, 2000, 
the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Spot silver transactions will be made only in local currency, it  
added. A futures market will follow two or three years later. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar plan to develop a gold market is likely to follow, the  
report cited Liu Shan'an, deputy director of the Gold Economic 
Development Research Center, as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	After decades of scarcity China now has a silver surplus. The  
government opened a market in silver jewelry trading in 1996 to 
help boost demand. It will continue to purchase silver from 
producers until the end of this year, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	It said that silver exports would remain under central bank  
control and that the bank planned to begin setting a quota on such 
exports next year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
